<subSubSection pageId="35" pageNumber="36" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="35.[151,1437,150,1978]" pageId="35" pageNumber="36">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,322,186,212]" pageId="35" pageNumber="36">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
Small slender species with typical labral shape. Resembling 
<taxonomicName authorityName="W. Horn" authorityYear="1900" box="[1002,1110,187,212]" class="Insecta" family="Carabidae" genus="Heptodonta" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="35" pageNumber="36" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="arrowi">
<emphasis box="[1002,1110,187,212]" italics="true" pageId="35" pageNumber="36">H. arrowi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, but distinguishable by acute aedeagal apex, wavy diagonal spines row within aedeagal inner sac (best seen in right lateral aspect), slender elytral and pronotal shape, finer pronotal striation (
<figureCitation box="[659,730,259,285]" captionStart="FIGURES 1–7" captionStartId="5.[151,264,1827,1851]" captionTargetBox="[177,1392,191,1791]" captionTargetId="figure-15@5.[177,1410,181,1803]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURES 1–7. 1–2—anterior elytra: 1—Heptodonta melanopyga (Schaum, 1862), ♀, Philippines, Luzon, Banaue (PSCH); 2—H. mindoroensis Cassola, 2000, ♂, Philippines, Mindoro, Mt. Halcon (JWCW). 3–4—pronotum: 3—H. arrowi W. Horn, 1900, ♂, Myanmar, Magway Region, Pyon Village (SGCH); 4—Heptodonta horii sp. nov., ♂, holotype, Myanmar, Bago Re- gion, Chanthakwin (JWCW); 5–7—head: 5—Heptodonta tempesta sp. nov., ♂, holotype, India, Meghalaya, Balpakram NP (JWCW); 6—Heptodonta pulchella (Hope, 1831), ♂, Nepal, Bagmati, Sollenta-Dhading (JWCW); 7—Heptodonta schuelei sp. nov., ♂, holotype, India, Meghalaya, Cherrapunjee (JWCW). Scales: 1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4578783" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4578783/files/figure.png" pageId="35" pageNumber="36">Fig. 4</figureCitation>
), and considerably reduced third labral teeth. There might be some confusion with exceptionally small specimens of 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Hope" baseAuthorityYear="1831" box="[771,909,295,321]" class="Insecta" family="Carabidae" genus="Heptodonta" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="35" pageNumber="36" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="pulchella">
<emphasis box="[771,909,295,321]" italics="true" pageId="35" pageNumber="36">H. pulchella</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Chaudoir" authorityYear="1865" box="[923,1046,295,320]" class="Insecta" family="Carabidae" genus="Heptodonta" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="35" pageNumber="36" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="eugenia">
<emphasis box="[923,1046,295,320]" italics="true" pageId="35" pageNumber="36">H. eugenia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, or 
<taxonomicName authorityName="W. Horn" authorityYear="1908" box="[1090,1233,295,321]" class="Insecta" family="Carabidae" genus="Heptodonta" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="35" pageNumber="36" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="vermifera">
<emphasis box="[1090,1233,295,321]" italics="true" pageId="35" pageNumber="36">H. vermifera</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, but in contrast to those species the labrum of 
<taxonomicName box="[459,547,331,357]" class="Insecta" family="Carabidae" genus="Heptodonta" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="35" pageNumber="36" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="horii" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[459,547,331,357]" italics="true" pageId="35" pageNumber="36">H. horii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[553,642,331,357]" pageId="35" pageNumber="36">
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[553,642,331,357]" pageId="35" pageNumber="36" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
has a specific semicircular shape in males and semicircular-trapezoidal shape in females, and the elytra have slightly reduced microsculpture and dense, shallowly fused punctures. Unlike 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Hope" baseAuthorityYear="1831" box="[201,340,403,429]" class="Insecta" family="Carabidae" genus="Heptodonta" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="35" pageNumber="36" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="pulchella">
<emphasis box="[201,340,403,429]" italics="true" pageId="35" pageNumber="36">H. pulchella</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authorityName="W. Horn" authorityYear="1908" box="[396,540,403,429]" class="Insecta" family="Carabidae" genus="Heptodonta" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="35" pageNumber="36" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="vermifera">
<emphasis box="[396,540,403,429]" italics="true" pageId="35" pageNumber="36">H. vermifera</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, the mesepisternum is violet. It is distinct from 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Chaudoir" authorityYear="1865" box="[1084,1208,403,428]" class="Insecta" family="Carabidae" genus="Heptodonta" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="35" pageNumber="36" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="eugenia">
<emphasis box="[1084,1208,403,428]" italics="true" pageId="35" pageNumber="36">H. eugenia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by dense anteapical punctures on elytra, and from 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="White" baseAuthorityYear="1844" box="[494,636,439,465]" class="Insecta" family="Carabidae" genus="Heptodonta" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="35" pageNumber="36" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="posticalis">
<emphasis box="[494,636,439,465]" italics="true" pageId="35" pageNumber="36">H. posticalis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, which has a similar elytral surface, by different labral shape and total body length under 
<quantity box="[362,464,474,501]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.15" pageId="35" pageNumber="36" unit="mm" value="11.5">11.5 mm</quantity>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
